node.text:
If there is one thing that NEEDS to be canceled it’s diet culture.
.
Dieting takes up so much time and energy and 95-97 percent of people will lose weight in the short term and then gain it back in the long term.
.
Diet culture also puts crappy messaging in our heads labeling foods as good vs bad which can lead to both restricting and bingeing.
.
It also promotes ‘body ideals’ and is highly fatphobic-this makes people literally try to fight their biology and suppress their weight below its natural set point range which is NOT healthy and also serves to suppress life experiences.
.
Cake baked by an amazing former client. Raise your hand if you think diet culture should be canceled. 🙋🏼‍♀️🙋🏼‍♀️🙋🏼‍♀️
.

node.text:
Repost art and caption from @paigepayne_creations 
.
Posted @withregram • @paigepayne_creations
.
 “Edit: prints are available on my website! 

Broken and beautiful. I’ve had some hard body-image days recently, and so I knew it was time to paint my feelings out. This piece is inspired by a Japanese pottery technique called Kintsugi (金継ぎ, "golden joinery"). The broken pottery is fixed using a gold lacquer, which reattaches the pieces together and makes it whole again. 

The purpose of this technique is to honor and highlight the history of the piece. It treats the breakage the piece has endured as something of beauty. I have been enraptured with this technique ever since I learned about it many years ago in my pottery class. It makes me emotional to just talk about. 

I chose to recreate one of my most popular pieces, and add some Kintsugi to the figures. We are all broken in different ways. Some of us get injured physically, some of us deal with mental health illness, others of us fight eating disorders and feel at war with our body. For years I have felt like my mind was broken. Struggling with anxiety and depression, I have felt broken so many times. But I believe that our struggles and our broken pieces make us all the more beautiful. 

I also wanted to create something that reiterates a message I am so passionate about - that ALL bodies are beautiful, no matter the size, shape, or color. When I have a daughter one day, I can’t wait to hang this in her room to remind her of that. We are ALL lumpy, bumpy, ‘imperfect’, and broken in certain ways. And all of those things are what make us so perfectly whole.”
.

.
I know it’s so hard AND it’s important to try to eat anyway and to seek professional help!
.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jennifer Rollin, MSW, LCSW-C on August 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Jennifer Rollin @jennifer_rollin We need to be talking about the challenges that exist for folks in larger bodies who are recovering from eating disorders. For ex, I follow someone in recovery in a larger body on TikTok who gets hate comment after hate comment, simply for existing in her body.'.

node.text:
As clinicians we need to both acknowledge our privilege (if we live in smaller bodies) and validate that for those recovering in a larger body they face systemic fat phobia.
.
I’ve had clients in larger bodies recover AND we have to talk about the barriers that exist and make things difficult-such as poor medical care that may encourage the ED, bullying online, spaces and clothing that are not accessible to their bodies.
.
If you’re recovering in a larger body-YOUR BODY IS NOT WRONG. Society is.
.
Myself and my amazing team are HAES and fat positive therapists (ie we don’t believe folks in larger bodies should just be accepted-they deserve to be celebrated). 💃🏼
.

node.text:
SAY IT LOUDER FOR THE PEOPLE IN THE BACK! 🎤⠀⠀
.
You can’t tell if someone has an eating disorder by looking at them, and specific diagnoses don’t have a “look.”⠀
.
Eating disorders are mental illnesses that sometimes have physical symptoms and effects – someone's weight or appearance doesn't define their struggle.⠀
.
You can have an eating disorder at ANY weight.
.
